      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(providers): release stream reader lock after classifying SDK stream body",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`src/agents/provider-transport-fetch.ts` calls `reader.cancel()` in the finally block of `classifyOpenAISdkStreamBody` but does not call `reader.releaseLock()`. Per the Streams specification, `reader.cancel()` rejects pending reads but does NOT release the lock — `releaseLock()` is required to allow other consumers to acquire the cloned stream.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `src/agents/provider-transport-fetch.ts`: add `reader.releaseLock()` wrapped in try/catch after `reader.cancel()` in the finally block\n- `test/_proof_providers_stream_lock.mts`: Web Streams lock lifecycle proof (5 PASS, 0 FAIL)\n\nLabel: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Real behavior proof — Web Streams lock lifecycle (L2)\n\n```\n$ node --import tsx test/_proof_providers_stream_lock.mts\n\nPASS  fresh stream: not locked\nPASS  after getReader: stream is locked\nPASS  after reader.cancel(): stream still locked :: locked=true\nPASS  after reader.releaseLock(): stream unlocked :: locked=false\nPASS  new reader: can acquire after lock released :: locked=true\n\n[proof] 5 PASS, 0 FAIL\n```\n\n`reader.cancel()` alone does NOT release the ReadableStream lock. Per the WHATWG Streams specification §3.5.2, only `reader.releaseLock()` releases the lock and allows the stream to be consumed again.",
